---
// /packages/studio — flagship page for @ikenga/pkg-studio (com.ikenga.studio).
// Studio is built and runs in the shell, but is NOT yet published to the
// registry — this page is framed "coming to the registry" per DEC-1/G-21:
// no install command, no version claim. The in-app screens shown are the
// locked AI-filmmaker UI *concepts* (labelled as concepts), on the "The Forge"
// demo fixture. Copy source: plans/studio/pitch/ai-filmmakers.html +
// plans/studio/16-ai-filmmaker-workflow.md.
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import FeaturePage from '../../components/FeaturePage.astro';
import Button from '../../components/Button.astro';

const title = 'Studio — the orchestration spine for AI film';
const description =
	'Ikenga Studio turns a script into a finished cut on one board — breakdown, cast & world, storyboard, generation, and stitch — and orchestrates the generators you already use (fal.ai, Higgsfield, Google Flow). Built in the shell; coming to the registry.';
---

<Layout
	title={title}
	description={description}
	canonical="https://ikenga.dev/packages/studio/"
>
	<FeaturePage
		eyebrow="com.ikenga.studio · in the shell · Apache-2.0 · coming to the registry"
		title="the film lives <em>here.</em>"
		lede="Studio is the orchestration spine for AI film — script to breakdown to cast, storyboard, generation, and final cut, on one board. It doesn't replace the generators you use. It conducts them."
		problem="Studio runs in the Ikenga shell today and a real master MP4 has shipped end-to-end from it. It isn't published to the registry yet, so there's no install command here — it'll appear in the catalog the moment it ships. The in-app screens below are the locked interface concepts, shown on the 'The Forge' demo film."
		docsHref="/docs/studio/"
		catalogHref="/packages/"
	>

		<!-- Beat 1: the problem -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">The tools make shots. Nobody makes the film.</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Every AI generator is an island. Between them, the actual film — the through-line,
					the consistency, the record of what made each frame — falls on the floor.
				</p>
				<ul class="sk-list">
					<li><strong>Your cast &amp; world drift.</strong> No shared identity between the still you generated and the shot you animated. The face changes.</li>
					<li><strong>Prompts rot in spreadsheets.</strong> Past a few dozen shots, every prompt lives in a sheet nobody can keep in sync.</li>
					<li><strong>No record of the take.</strong> Which model, which seed, which settings made this clip? Re-editing means guessing.</li>
					<li><strong>Re-stitching by hand.</strong> Change the script or a character and the whole downstream chain is a manual re-run.</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 2: the spine -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Ikenga is the spine — not another generator</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Studio is one place for the script, the cast, the locations, the prompts, the clips,
					and the cut. It holds identity and provenance so nothing drifts and nothing is lost.
					It doesn't replace Higgsfield, Flow, or fal — it conducts them.
				</p>
				<p class="sk-body sd-tagline">
					Higgsfield, Flow, and fal make shots. <strong>Ikenga makes the film.</strong>
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 3: the pipeline -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Script to cut, one continuous board</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					One board carries the work from the first line of the script to the delivery master:
				</p>
				<pre class="sd-pipe sk-body"><code>Script → Breakdown → Refs &amp; Cast → Storyboard → Generate → Stitch &amp; Edit</code></pre>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Studio owns the authoritative render and approval state for every shot; a groundwork
					<a href="/docs/groundwork/profiles/">film</a> plan mirrors it for production management.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 4: the surfaces (concept screens) -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Six surfaces, one project</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					These are the locked interface concepts, shown on the wordless demo short
					<em>“The Forge”</em> — Adaora forging an iron mask through the night.
				</p>

				<figure class="sd-shot">
					<img src="/assets/studio/breakdown-b.png" alt="Studio breakdown — a script split into beats and shots with extracted characters, locations, and props" loading="lazy" width="1440" height="900" />
					<figcaption class="sk-body sd-shot__cap"><strong>Breakdown.</strong> Paste a script; it splits into beats and shots and pulls every character, location, and prop into a reference checklist — with the fal-vs-handoff plan decided per shot. <span class="sd-concept">concept</span></figcaption>
				</figure>

				<figure class="sd-shot">
					<img src="/assets/studio/canvas-gen-b.png" alt="Studio storyboard canvas — shots as cells generating live on two tracks, with running spend in a dock" loading="lazy" width="1440" height="900" />
					<figcaption class="sk-body sd-shot__cap"><strong>Storyboard canvas.</strong> Shots land as cells and generate in place — fal on Track A (seed-locked, cost shown), a Higgsfield handoff on Track B — with running spend in the dock. <span class="sd-concept">concept</span></figcaption>
				</figure>

				<figure class="sd-shot">
					<img src="/assets/studio/cast-world-c.png" alt="Studio Cast & World — seed-locked anchors with a continuity thread showing every shot each appears in" loading="lazy" width="1440" height="900" />
					<figcaption class="sk-body sd-shot__cap"><strong>Cast &amp; World.</strong> Each principal becomes a seed-locked <em>anchor</em>; a continuity thread shows every shot it appears in. The anti-drift heart — the face doesn't change from shot one to shot forty. <span class="sd-concept">concept</span></figcaption>
				</figure>

				<figure class="sd-shot">
					<img src="/assets/studio/cell-gen-a.png" alt="Studio cell — a generation console with prompt, anchor chips, engine picker, locked seed, living preview and an A/B variants tray" loading="lazy" width="1440" height="900" />
					<figcaption class="sk-body sd-shot__cap"><strong>Cell.</strong> Open a shot into a generation console — editable prompt, anchor-ref chips, engine picker, locked seed, a living preview, and an A/B variants tray. Pick the keeper; it lands on the board with full provenance. <span class="sd-concept">concept</span></figcaption>
				</figure>

				<figure class="sd-shot">
					<img src="/assets/studio/ledger-a.png" alt="Studio shot ledger — per-shot engine, model, seed, cost and variant with a running budget meter" loading="lazy" width="1440" height="900" />
					<figcaption class="sk-body sd-shot__cap"><strong>Shot ledger.</strong> Per shot: the engine, model, seed, cost, and variant, with a running budget meter. fal rows are cost-tracked; Higgsfield handoff rows are marked manual. The spreadsheet, native to the board. <span class="sd-concept">concept</span></figcaption>
				</figure>

				<figure class="sd-shot">
					<img src="/assets/studio/handoff-a.png" alt="Studio Track B handoff — a shaped per-shot prompt package for an API-less tool, with a clip ingest-back dropzone" loading="lazy" width="1440" height="900" />
					<figcaption class="sk-body sd-shot__cap"><strong>Handoff (Track B).</strong> For web-only tools with no API, Studio shapes a per-shot prompt package — ref image, aspect, duration, camera move — you generate in Higgsfield or Flow, and drop the returned clip back onto the shot. <span class="sd-concept">concept</span></figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 5: two tracks -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Two tracks, one board</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Automate what should be automatic; keep your hands on what's directorial. Both land on
					the same shot with the same provenance.
				</p>
				<div class="sd-tracks">
					<div class="sd-track">
						<p class="sd-track__tag sk-eyebrow">Track A — Studio generates</p>
						<p class="sk-body sd-track__line">
							Studio calls the generator directly through <strong>fal.ai</strong> — seed-locked,
							cost-tracked, the result lands on the shot. Best for stills, character &amp;
							location plates, and fast previews. FLUX · Kling · Veo · Wan · Hailuo · LTX.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="sd-track">
						<p class="sd-track__tag sk-eyebrow">Track B — you direct</p>
						<p class="sk-body sd-track__line">
							Web-app tools with no public API. Studio hands you a shaped per-shot prompt
							package; you generate and drop the clip back onto the shot. Best for directorial
							craft. Higgsfield · Google Flow · Sora · Midjourney.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 6: status -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Where it stands</h2>
				<p class="sk-body"><strong>Shipping today.</strong> Script → board → render → export runs end to end — a real master MP4 has shipped from it. Storyboard canvas, shot &amp; camera metadata, 16:9 / 9:16 / 1:1 framing, FFmpeg stitch with music beds, seven video archetypes, and a ~40-tool MCP surface (the board is fully agent-drivable).</p>
				<p class="sk-body"><strong>Building — staged.</strong> The fal adapter and prompt handoff (the generation spine); breakdown, character / location lock, and the shot ledger; AI-film archetypes and the groundwork <a href="/docs/groundwork/profiles/">film</a> profile for production planning.</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 7: plan it here -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Plan it in Groundwork. Shoot it in Studio.</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					The groundwork <a href="/docs/groundwork/profiles/">film</a> profile owns pre-production —
					logline, treatment, cast bible, lookbook, shotlist, budget — then hands off to Studio,
					which owns execution. The <a href="/docs/groundwork/film-workflow/">idea-to-cut guide</a>
					walks the whole loop.
				</p>
				<figure class="sd-shot">
					<img src="/assets/studio/lookbook-ember-noir.png" alt="The Forge — Ember-noir lookbook: palette and grade, scene-mood frames, the anti-drift anchor set, lens and grain notes, and a title treatment" loading="lazy" width="1440" height="4210" />
					<figcaption class="sk-body sd-shot__cap">
						The Ember-noir lookbook a <code>film</code> plan produces — palette, scene-mood frames,
						the anchor set, and title treatment — locked before a single shot generates.
					</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- See also -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">See also</h2>
				<div class="sd-links">
					<Button href="/docs/studio/" variant="ghost">Studio docs</Button>
					<Button href="/docs/groundwork/film-workflow/" variant="ghost">The idea-to-cut guide</Button>
					<Button href="/packages/groundwork" variant="ghost">Groundwork</Button>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

	</FeaturePage>
</Layout>

<style>
	.sd-tagline {
		font-family: var(--site-font-display);
		font-size: 1.25rem;
		color: var(--site-fg);
		margin-top: var(--space-4);
	}
	.sd-pipe {
		background: var(--site-surface);
		border: 1px solid var(--site-border);
		border-radius: var(--radius-md, 6px);
		padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6);
		overflow-x: auto;
		font-family: var(--site-font-mono);
		font-size: 0.875rem;
		line-height: 1.6;
		color: var(--site-fg);
		margin: 0 0 var(--space-5);
	}
	.sd-pipe code {
		font-family: inherit;
		font-size: inherit;
		color: inherit;
		background: none;
		padding: 0;
	}

	.sd-shot {
		margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
	}
	.sd-shot img {
		display: block;
		width: 100%;
		height: auto;
		border: 1px solid var(--site-border);
		border-radius: var(--radius-md, 6px);
		background: var(--site-surface);
	}
	.sd-shot__cap {
		margin: var(--space-3) 0 0;
		font-size: 0.875rem;
		color: var(--site-faint, var(--site-fg));
	}
	.sd-concept {
		display: inline-block;
		margin-left: var(--space-2);
		font-family: var(--site-font-mono);
		font-size: 0.6875rem;
		letter-spacing: 0.08em;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		color: var(--site-muted);
		border: 1px solid var(--site-border-strong);
		border-radius: var(--radius-sm, 4px);
		padding: 0.1em 0.5em;
		vertical-align: 0.1em;
	}

	.sd-tracks {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(18rem, 1fr));
		gap: var(--space-4);
		margin: var(--space-4) 0 0;
	}
	.sd-track {
		background: var(--site-surface);
		border: 1px solid var(--site-border);
		border-radius: var(--radius-md, 6px);
		padding: var(--space-5);
	}
	.sd-track__tag {
		margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
	}
	.sd-track__line {
		margin: 0;
		font-size: 0.9375rem;
	}

	.sd-links {
		display: flex;
		gap: var(--space-3);
		flex-wrap: wrap;
	}
</style>
